[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(2) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Abiding in his tents . . . —",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "encamped according to the order prescribed for the respective tribes. The cognate noun is rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "tabernacles ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 24:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And the spirit of God came upon him.—In regard to the two former utterances, it is said that Jehovah put a word in the mouth of Balaam (Numbers 23:5; Numbers 23:15). In the present case the Spirit of God came upon (or, over) him. The same expression is used of the messengers of Saul (1Samuel 19:20), and of Saul himself (Ibid, Numbers 24:23). The prophecy of Caiaphas (John 11:15) affords another instance of the sovereign power of the Spirit as displayed through the medium of wicked men.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And the spirit of God came upon him.—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "In regard to the two former utterances, it is said that Jehovah put a word in the mouth of Balaam (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 23:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 23:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). In the present case the Spirit of God came upon (or, over) him. The same expression is used of the messengers of Saul (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Samuel 19:20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and of Saul himself (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Ibid, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 24:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). The prophecy of Caiaphas (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 11:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") affords another instance of the sovereign power of the Spirit as displayed through the medium of wicked men.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Numbers 24:2-3",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 24:2-3",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The Spirit of God came upon him — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And is it likely that the Spirit of God would have come upon a sorcerer or enchanter? A prophetic influence from God came upon him, whereby he was enabled to foresee future events, and inspired to utter the following words: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The man whose eyes are open — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Some, confounding ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "שׁתם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "shetum, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "סתם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "שׂתם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "setum, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "would translate the words, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Whose eyes are ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "were shut, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for which there does not seem to be sufficient authority. The Seventy render them, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ο αληθινως ορων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "seeing truly. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "His eyes indeed had been shut, and he had been blind and stupid, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "having eyes but not seeing, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "nor understanding; but God had opened them in a peculiar and prophetical manner. Hence the prophets were called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "seers, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "from God’s having opened their eyes.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "24:1-9 Now Balaam spake not his own sense, but the language of the Spirit that came upon him. Many have their eyes open who have not their hearts open; are enlightened, but not sanctified. That knowledge which puffs men up with pride, will but serve to light them to hell, whither many go with their eyes open. The blessing is nearly the same as those given before. He admires in Israel, their beauty. The righteous, doubtless, is more excellent than his neighbour. Their fruitfulness and increase. Their honour and advancement. Their power and victory. He looks back upon what had been done for them. Their power and victory. He looks back upon what had been done for them. Their courage and security. The righteous are bold as a lion, not when assaulting others, but when at rest, because God maketh them to dwell in safety. Their influence upon their neighbours. God takes what is done to them, whether good or evil, as done to himself.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Balaam gazed over the camp of Israel that stretched before him, and allowed the spectacle to work its own influence upon him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2. he saw Israel abiding in his tents according to their tribes—that is, in the orderly distribution of the camp (Nu 2:1-34).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "the spirit of God came upon him—Before the regular ministry of the prophets was instituted, God made use of various persons as the instruments through whom He revealed His will, and Balaam was one of these (De 23:5).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
